{"parse":{"title":"Grateful dead (folklore)","pageid":12827691,"revid":859408772,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">For the American rock band, see <a href=\"/wiki/Grateful_Dead\" title=\"Grateful Dead\">Grateful Dead</a>.</div>\n<p><b>Grateful dead</b>  (or <b>grateful ghost</b>) is a <a href=\"/wiki/Folklore\" title=\"Folklore\">folktale</a> present in many cultures throughout the world. The most common story involves a traveler who encounters a corpse of someone who never received a proper <a href=\"/wiki/Burial\" title=\"Burial\">burial</a>, typically stemming from an unpaid debt.<sup id=\"cite_ref-encybrit_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-encybrit-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-cscmu_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-cscmu-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The traveler then either pays off the dead person's debt or pays for burial. The traveler is later rewarded or has their life saved by a person or animal who is actually the soul of the dead person; the grateful dead is a form of the <a href=\"/wiki/Donor_(fairy_tale)\" title=\"Donor (fairy tale)\">donor</a>.\n</p><p>The \"grateful dead\" story is <a href=\"/wiki/Aarne%E2%80%93Thompson\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Aarne\u2013Thompson\">Aarne\u2013Thompson</a>\u2013Uther type 505.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>An ancient Egyptian text explains the <a href=\"/wiki/Golden_Rule\" title=\"Golden Rule\">principle of reciprocity</a> in which the deceased calls for a blessing on the person who remembers his name and helps him into a happy afterlife:\n</p>\n<blockquote><p>But if there be a man, any one whomsoever, who beholdeth this writing and causeth my soul and my name to become established among those who are blessed, let it be done for him likewise after his final arriving (at the end of life's voyage) in recompense for what was done by him for me, Osiris.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup></p></blockquote>\n<p>One variant is the <a href=\"/wiki/Book_of_Tobit\" title=\"Book of Tobit\">Book of Tobit</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-hibbard74_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-hibbard74-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>  The <a href=\"/wiki/Chivalric_romance\" title=\"Chivalric romance\">chivalric romance</a> <i><a href=\"/wiki/Amadas\" title=\"Amadas\">Amadas</a></i> has the title knight pay his last coins for such a burial.<sup id=\"cite_ref-hibbard74_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-hibbard74-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>  It appears in various fairy tales, such as the Italian <i><a href=\"/wiki/Fair_Brow\" title=\"Fair Brow\">Fair Brow</a></i>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> the Swedish <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Bird_%27Grip%27\" title=\"The Bird &#39;Grip&#39;\">The Bird 'Grip'</a></i> and <a href=\"/wiki/Hans_Christian_Andersen\" title=\"Hans Christian Andersen\">H. C. Andersen</a>'s <i>The Traveling Companion</i>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Grateful_dead_(folklore)&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-encybrit-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-encybrit_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9037771/grateful-dead#23476.hook\">\"Grateful dead\"</a>. <i>Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica</i>. 2007<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2007-12-14</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Encyclop%C3%A6dia+Britannica&amp;rft.atitle=Grateful+dead&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.britannica.com%2Feb%2Farticle-9037771%2Fgrateful-dead%2323476.hook&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGrateful+dead+%28folklore%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-cscmu-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-cscmu_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.cs.cmu.edu/~mleone/gdead/faq/name.html\">\"Dead FAQ: How did they get the name?\"</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2007-12-14</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Dead+FAQ%3A+How+did+they+get+the+name%3F&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cs.cmu.edu%2F~mleone%2Fgdead%2Ffaq%2Fname.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGrateful+dead+%28folklore%29\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">D.L. Ashliman. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.pitt.edu/~dash/type0505.html\">\"The Grateful Dead:  folktales of Aarne\u2013Thompson\u2013Uther type 505\"</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2008-05-20</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=The+Grateful+Dead%3A++folktales+of+